1

00:00:00,570  -->  00:00:05,875
You now have gained some intuition for how the Central Limit Theorem works.

2

00:00:05,875  -->  00:00:09,214
But it doesn't work for all sampling distributions.

3

00:00:09,214  -->  00:00:14,785
Sure, a mean and proportion are normally distributed with large enough sample sizes.

4

00:00:14,785  -->  00:00:17,699
But what does it mean for a sample size to be large enough?

5

00:00:17,699  -->  00:00:20,214
Is a sample size of 10 large enough?

6

00:00:20,214  -->  00:00:23,160
Or 30? Or 100?

7

00:00:23,160  -->  00:00:28,759
You might memorize a list of statistics for which the Central Limit Theorem applies.

8

00:00:28,760  -->  00:00:31,755
It applies for the mean, and for proportions,

9

00:00:31,754  -->  00:00:33,935
and applies for the difference in means,

10

00:00:33,935  -->  00:00:35,925
and difference in proportions.

11

00:00:35,924  -->  00:00:37,699
However, the Central Limit Theorem doesn't

12

00:00:37,700  -->  00:00:40,175
apply to the sampling distribution for the variance,

13

00:00:40,174  -->  00:00:42,539
or for the correlation coefficient.

14

00:00:42,539  -->  00:00:46,329
It doesn't apply for the sampling distribution of the maximum value in a data set.

15

00:00:46,329  -->  00:00:48,929
With all the data being collected in the world,

16

00:00:48,929  -->  00:00:52,280
and tons of compute power available at our fingertips,

17

00:00:52,280  -->  00:00:56,524
the Central Limit Theorem is still useful for some sampling distributions.

18

00:00:56,524  -->  00:00:58,640
But instead of relying on this theorem,

19

00:00:58,640  -->  00:01:03,210
what if we just simulated whatever sampling distribution we were interested in instead?
